According to our standardized program, all patients with a clinical suspicion for aorto-iliac and/or infrainguinal ALI and/or upper limb ischemia underwent routine preoperative screening blood tests including creatine-phosphokinase (CPK) and D-dimer levels, along with chest radiograph and electrocardiogram (ECG). Preoperative computed tomography scan was performed to identify COVID-19 related pneumonia (Figure 1
). These studies were performed in the Emergency Room in order to avoid cross-contamination and unnecessary risk of viral spread. Patients with suspected aorto-iliac occlusion underwent computed-tomography angiography (CT-A) to assess the extent of disease and vessel sizing (Figure 2
A,B). Patients who presented with infrainguinal and/or upper limb occlusive disease underwent echo-color-Doppler evaluation of both the arterial and venous systems. Also, during the course of hospitalization all patients were screened for the identification of eventual cardiac emboli sources by means of transthoracic echocardiography. Operative risk profile was defined using a multidisciplinary evaluation which included the physical examination and laboratory blood tests.
